History

The region has an ancient history, including the Median Empire, which ruled the region for several centuries. In 550 BC, Cyrus the Great defeated the Median king Astyages, who ruled over the region and established the Achaemenid Empire, which extended far beyond the present-day boundaries of Iran. The Sassanid Empire (224–651) also encompassed the region.

In the Islamic era, the region was part of the province of Rayy, a major political and cultural center in the Islamic period. Rayy was the capital of this province from the 8th to the 10th centuries.

In the 13th century, the Mongols under Genghis Khan invaded and destroyed Rayy. The region then came under the control of the Ilkhanate and then the Timurid Empire. In the 16th century, the Safavid dynasty established its capital at Tabriz, where it ruled until the 18th century.

During the Qajar dynasty, the region was divided into two parts, with the eastern half forming part of the province of Azerbaijan and the western half being part of the province of Zanjan. However, during the Pahlavi era, these two provinces were merged into one and renamed Azerbaijan.

Geography

Azerbaijan province lies at the north-west corner of Iran and has a strategic position bordering the Republic of Azerbaijan, Armenia, and Turkey. It is bordered by East Azerbaijan province to the south and Zanjan and West Azerbaijan provinces to the east. The Caspian Sea lies to the north, and Aras River forms part of the western border with Turkey.
